               <msContents>
                  <summary>This is a very fine “Old Testament” manuscript in Ge‘ez, likely produced
                     in a scriptorium by the hand of at least ten scribes. The date of the work is
                     written in the first colon at the end of 2 Kings: the 27th year of Särs’ä
                     Dəngəl reign. Much of Micah is missing – the first five verses of the book are
                     included – and much of Joel is missing, with only the last very and colophon of
                     the latter remaining. The second colophon states that the work was translated
                     by Jacob the Israelite from Hebrew to Ge‘ez, and was written by the scribe
                     Waldä Giyorgis for Queen Maryam Səna [wife of <persName key="person_89015410"
                        >Sarsa Dengel, Negus of Ethiopia, -1597 </persName>]. Her name has since
                     been erased in many locations. The work contains some Amharic marginalia; the
                     concluding leaves <locus from="260" to="267"> ff. 260-267</locus> contain sales
                     contracts and property listings, written in Amharic, of members of Ethiopian
                     nobility, dated roughly to 1750-1780.</summary>
